Polynomials are functions like lines, parabolas, cubics, etc. The best
examples to consider are horizontal lines and parabolas.

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  No horizontal line crosses the \emph{x}-axis.
\end{itemize}

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{MER_MATH110_December_2012_Question_2d_horizontal_line.jpg}
\caption{MER MATH110 December 2012 Question 2d horizontal line.jpg}
\end{figure}

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  The graph of a parabola can be shifted so that it doesn't cross the
  \emph{x}-axis.
\end{itemize}

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{MER_MATH110_December_2012_Question_2d_parabola.jpg}
\caption{MER MATH110 December 2012 Question 2d parabola.jpg}
\end{figure}

Either of these would be a counter-example, so the statement is false.
